originalText.text: I had a wonderful experience with Leke Abiodun as my therapist at Spear. I needed shoulder therapy and he mapped out a progressive methodical game plan to nurse me back to my previous function. He was kind, very pleasant and real. When my next body part falls apart, I have no hesitation in calling on him once again.

originalText.text: I came to SPEAR after having to take six weeks off (femoral stress fracture). As a long distance runner, it was important I found the right care. Camryn & Kate made it easy to trust them with their knowledge and confidence in my injury and steps to recovery. I continued to go here for 2+ months gaining strength and learning new methods for healthy running. I am now back on my feet and feeling great, thanks to the team. Recommend!!

originalText.text:
I do not see how anyone could have anything good to say about SPEAR. While I have only been to the 16th Street location, the business model is very clear and it maximizes profits over clients/patients.

You do not work with a physical therapist. You “work” with an assistant. No information is available on the training of assistants but my guess is that they do not have any training at all. Not that it matters because neither the physical therapists nor the assistants stay with you. The assistants read off a “post it” note as to what you should do and walk away. No one is supervising. No one is watching that your form is correct. And the area is jammed with people because when you do not offer one-on-one care or supervision, you can process a lot of people.

I’ve read positive reviews but I also noticed that very few of the people mentioned in the reviews are there any longer. My guess is that anyone who is good and cares about the client/patient leaves as soon as they can.

Even the layout of the 16th Street location screams profits over patients. It is a two level location with a very narrow entryway not suitable to wheelchairs or walkers. There is a very steep flight of stairs to the therapy area (and yes a tucked away elevator.) Lockers are so low the locks are below knee level and I am only 5 ft 2 in. So beware if you have back or knee pain. But they jam a lot into very little space. Good for profits not people.

And just a few specifics. I went to SPEAR for infrequent intermittent shoulder pain. My MD told me it was highly treatable with PT. My assigned physical therapist was Himani. On my first session, she spent 2 minutes with me and the left for 10 minutes to speak with another patient. She spent another 3 minutes with me, gave me 2 exercises for home and that was it.  I was with her for 10 minutes.

My next appointment was cancelled the day of the appointment.

Before my next appointment I developed severe back pain on the side of the shoulder being treated. I never had pain in that area and it was knee buckling sharp persistent pain. I could not even take a full breath in. Truth is I’m not sure it was the exercises or putting away holiday decorations.

I went to my second session and an assistant came over with a “post it” of what I should do.  Himani did not even speak with me or inquire as to how the exercises went or how I was feeling. No interaction whatsoever.  Because of my back pain, I asked to speak with her. Even though it was my appointment time, I had to wait. Then she was about to speak to me and disappeared for 5 minutes. When she returned, she shrugged and said it could happen and disappeared again. I was at the facility for 30 minutes and at least half of the time was waiting while the assistant gave instructions to other clients. And at the end of the session, Himani never came out to check on me . I was just told I could go. She did not ask how my back was feeling or how the session went.  No at home follow up.

The complete and total lack of interest and indifference was truly shocking.

10 years ago I had foot surgery and had physical therapy and that care was phenomenal. Now if only I could remember the name of the facility.

DO NOT GO TO SPEAR!

originalText.text:
Farhan R at SPEAR has been a fantastic therapist since our very first session (I'm in the 20's now). I came in with a significant rehabilitation requirement and Farhan has, day-in and day-out, worked hard to get me back to where I need to be. Our daily sessions advance on or ahead of track and he provides comprehensive at-home exercises to support a speedy recovery. He has been flexible with scheduling even when I have cancelled the night before.

Regarding quality of care, Farhan has helped me re-build strength at a brisk but cautious pace, and always checks in as to my limits. He identified and has meaningfully corrected a nerve issue (by-product of surgery). Farhan's attention to detail has allowed me to recover faster and tailor the recovery plan that works best for me. I feel fortunate to have Farhan as my therapist!

The location itself on 16th & 8th, the bright and engaging staff, and comradery with other patients makes SPEAR my top choice today and recommendation for others.

I will be seeing Farhan as long as my insurance will allow. Highly recommend!

originalText.text: I work as a care assistant for one of Leke's patients. His work with her has been an amazing. He guides her confidently so she feels safe (they work on balance) and lets her do exercises at her own pace while continuously challenging her. I can see a direct, positive correlation between her work with Leke and her well being in her everyday life. Thank you Leke and the entire Spear staff!
